aoism, Wiccan, Pastafarian, etc.). &#10;The opposition towards religion in schools should be directed at teaching or promoting a certain religion within a classroom setting (ie. classroom-based prayer), or the teaching of religious interpretations of scientific disciplines. Students should be allowed some expression of their religious beliefs as long as it is not imposed on the rest of the student body or delivered as fact within a classroom setting. I can see how people might be apprehensive towards allowing this at all for fear that it might be a slippery slope towards religious-based education in the public school system. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="936" language="en" documentId="1484" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Boreal Owl" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1484" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="342"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="343" end="936"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>